Legally speaking, however, the #Saami in Sweden were still seen as the actual owners of their lands well into 1885, as long as these lands were considered to be inhabited.

The large-scale Swedish colonisation of #Saami territories truly began during the 17th century, and ever since, the Saami have been forced to accept intrusions on their lands and the thefts of their property by Fenno-Scandian settlers.
... so that the water would stream out of the #Saami protesters' mouths when they surfaced, as is the preferred method [of torture] among miners."

In a document from 1655, one example of how #Saami men were tortured is given;

"We tied the [Saami protesters] with a pair of reins whereupon we threw them into the ice-cold river multiple times, dragging them underwater ...

The Swedish queen Kristina used #Saami citizens who were unable to pay taxes as slaves in her silver mine Nasa when she despite cruel forms of torture failed to employ as many Saami as needed to carry out the troublesome task of transporting the silver from the mine to the coast.

Taxes varied throughout history for a number of reasons, but it is worth mentioning that until 1695 #Saami men and women were taxed on an individual basis, despite being members of a communal economy.

... and in 1534 the Swedish king Gustav Vasa stated that the #Saami were the owners of their ancestral homelands but liable to pay taxes to the Swedish state, regardless of whether or not they were already taxed by Norway.
Most sources indicate that any actual attempts by #colonisers to settle on #Saami territories before the 16th century were sporadic, ...

Back then it is said that an earl, acting on behalf of the English king, was living in Troms, Norway, who forced the #indigenous #Saami to pay taxes to England. Similar stories tell of Icelandic Vikings who used to attack the Norwegian coast back in the 13th century.

... and archaeological finds from the north of Norway and Sweden show that this presence dates back as far as 10,000 years. 

However, judging from historical records, the actual colonisation of #Saami territories by foreign states did not begin before the early 9th century.

Since time immemorial the #Saami and their ancestors have been resident in an area which stretches from the Russian Kola Peninsula in the east across northern Finland, Sweden and Norway down to Idre in central Sweden and Elg√• in Norway to the southwest ...

400 years ago, #indigenous #Saami reindeer herders were used as slaves in the N√°sav√°rre silver mine, which straddles the border between Sweden and Norway. Despite this historical injustice, the area has always functioned as a vital reindeer grazing area for five communities.
